description: From Middle English immensurable, from Old French, from Latin immēnsūrābilis, from im- (“not”) (variant form of in-) + mēnsūra (“measure”) + -bilis (“able”).

adjectives.description: immensurable (comparative more immensurable, superlative most immensurable)

entries.meaning: unmeasurable, immeasurable; not able to be measured, therefore connoting extremely large
